# clean-code-guard (Cursor rule)

A second-pass quality gate for generated or changed **production code**. Run it
after the first implementation pass and fix violations before delivery. This
does not replace `dart analyze` / `flutter test` — those handle mechanical
verification; this is the judgement layer.

Full skill (canonical source, with `references/`):
[`.agents/skills/clean-code-guard/SKILL.md`](../../.agents/skills/clean-code-guard/SKILL.md).
Read it (and the linked `references/`) when you need the reasoning or citation
behind a rule, or when in review mode.

## Always-applied imperatives

**Functions and names**
1. Names reveal intent — no bare `data`, `result`, `temp`, `item`, `value`, `manager`, `utils`, or `handle_*`/`process_*` without a qualifier.
2. Functions stay small (~≤20 lines, one level of abstraction, one thing).
3. Four arguments is the ceiling; at five, introduce a config object. No boolean flag args — split into two functions.
4. Command/query separation: a function returns a value *or* has a side effect, not both.

**Comments and structure**
5. Comments explain *why*, not *what*. Delete paraphrasing comments, step-number scaffolding, and commented-out code.
6. Match the file's existing style — read the file and one neighbor before writing; don't introduce a second pattern.

**SOLID**
7. One actor per module (SRP).
8. Extend via new code, not edits to existing type-tag branches (OCP).
9. No subclass refuses its parent's contract (LSP).
10. Abstractions live with the client, not the implementation (DIP).

**DRY, KISS, YAGNI**
11. Delete duplicated *knowledge*, not duplicated *text*.
12. The wrong abstraction is worse than duplication — re-inline before re-abstracting.
13. Complexity ceiling: cyclomatic ≤10, nesting ≤5.
14. No speculative parameters, flags, interfaces, or base classes without a present-day caller.

**AI-specific guardrails (highest leverage)**
15. Never swallow errors in broad catch-all handlers; catch only what you can recover from, else propagate.
16. No defensive guards for cases the type/contract already excludes.
17. Verify every import and external call against the installed version (check the lockfile / package) — do not invent APIs.
18. No hardcoded "success" returns or mock fixtures in production code; never weaken a test to make it pass.
19. Re-derive from spec instead of copy-from-similar (where off-by-one and null-semantic bugs enter).
20. Enumerate boundary cases (empty/one/many, off-by-one, unicode/byte) before writing them.
21. Strip dead code (unused imports/symbols, unreachable branches) before delivery.
22. Read before write — the target file, one neighbor, and project rules (CLAUDE.md / `.cursor/rules`); reuse existing helpers, error types, and logging.

## Tilawa specifics

Use the project's own gates as the mechanical layer: run `dart analyze` and the
relevant `flutter test test/features/<feature>/` after changes. Honour the
repo's `Either<Failure, T>` boundaries (rule 15) and design-token usage (no
hard-coded sizes/colors) when reviewing UI code.
